      "text": "Here is the English translation of the provided Maldivian text concerning property transfer laws:\n\n**Law on Transfer of Ownership**\n\n**(Including the 5th Amendment to this Law)**\n\n**Law on Transfer of Ownership**\n\n1.  If ownership of property is to be transferred to another party through gift, grant, or sale, excluding government transactions, it must be submitted to the court in accordance with the following points:\n    *   (a) It must be the property of the donor or seller.\n    *   (b) The donor or seller must appear before the court and request the transfer of ownership.\n    *   (c) If the party cannot appear in person due to a valid reason as stated in (b), they must appoint another party to appear on their behalf in the court session, in the presence of two just witnesses. When making such an appointment, a written document that fully explains the desired transfer of ownership according to Sharia principles must be prepared and signed by all four individuals (with their names and addresses clearly stated).\n    *   (d) The party accepting ownership must also act in accordance with the regulations stipulated in sections (b) and (c) of this article.\n    *   (e) Except for the circumstances mentioned in (l), when the appointed representative appears before the court, they must submit the written document signed by the four individuals as mentioned in section (c). Furthermore, the two witnesses mentioned in that document must also appear before the court and testify that the statement is true.\n    *   (l) If it is difficult to submit the written document signed by the four individuals as mentioned in (c) and (d) because the donor, seller, or recipient is abroad, they must appoint another party (with their full name and address clearly stated) to appear on their behalf in court. They must also submit a written document, prepared and signed according to Sharia principles, with the endorsement of an official body (such as a Notary Public or a Maldivian Embassy), which clearly states the appointment and the desired transfer or acceptance of ownership.\n    *   (k) If the ownership of any registered item or property, other than private land and buildings on that land, is being transferred, an official letter from the registering authority stating no objection to this transfer must be provided.\n\n2.  If, after transferring ownership through gift, grant, or sale, either party involved in the transaction wishes to bring the matter before the court, they must submit a document signed by both parties, along with the signatures of the witnesses present at the time of signing, to the court.\n\n3.  The report on the conclusion of court proceedings for ownership transfers, as per articles 1 and 2, shall be provided to the relevant parties immediately after the proceedings are concluded.\n\n4.  Any issue concerning an item or property whose ownership has been transferred according to this law shall only be brought before the court with the accompanying Sharia report of the concluded matter.\n\nLaw Number: 9/68\nCommencement Date: 01 July 1968\nAmendment Number: 5\n\nCopyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office.",
