      "text": "Here is the accurate English translation of the provided Maldivian text:\n\n**Laws of the Maldives**\n\n**Law Concerning the Demarcation of Boundaries of Properties and Land in Malé, and the Construction of Buildings and Structures on or near Boundaries, and the Cutting of Doors onto Streets**\n\n**(Including the 5th Amendment to this Law)**\n\n**Law Concerning the Demarcation of Boundaries of Properties and Land in Malé, and the Construction of Buildings and Structures on or near Boundaries, and the Cutting of Doors onto Streets**\n\n1.  All parties of every property or land must have boundaries demarcated or walled. Furthermore, any doors to be cut onto the street from the boundary wall or demarcation of a property facing the street, or any existing doors to be closed, must be done with the permission of the Malé Municipality.\n\n2.  Any wall on the boundary of a property or land must be erected with the permission of the Malé Municipality for wall construction.\n\n3.  No building or structure shall be constructed on or near the boundary of a property or land that has not been marked by the Malé Municipality for boundary demarcation.\n\n4.  Door leaves of gates on street-facing boundaries of properties or land, and door leaves of buildings, shall not open outwards onto the street from below 12 feet from the building.\n\n5.  (a) The construction of any eaves, concrete shelters, or any part of a building that protrudes onto the street shall be permitted only in accordance with the regulations established by the Ministry of Home Affairs, Housing and Environment, taking into account the width of the street.\n\n    (b) In situations where permission is granted under the regulations mentioned in section (a) of this article, the protrusion of eaves, concrete shelters, or any part of a building onto the street will only be permitted after considering the width of the street and the provisions of those regulations, as follows:\n        (1) From the ground up to a height of 20 feet, the protrusion from the building shall not extend more than 1 1/2 feet onto the street.\n        (2) From a height of more than 20 feet from the ground, the protrusion from the building shall not extend more than 4 feet onto the street.\n\n    (c) No eaves, concrete shelters, or any part of a building on streets less than 6 feet wide shall be permitted to protrude onto the street.\n\n6.  For properties or land situated at the intersection of two streets, if the corner joining the two streets has not been rounded and walled in accordance with the arrangements made by the Malé Municipality, any construction must be done within a designated area permitted by the Malé Municipality.\n\n7.  For properties or land situated at the intersection of two streets, if the corner joining the two streets has not yet been rounded, it must be rounded in accordance with the arrangements made by the Malé Municipality before the end of December 1988.\n\n8.  Notwithstanding the provisions of Article 5 of this Law regarding the outward placement of concrete shelters, concrete blocks, and similar structures within the specified measurements, the government reserves the right to acquire such structures for public purposes, such as road construction, after providing legal compensation.\n\nLaw Number: 54/78\nCommencement Date: 31 May 1978\nAmendment Number: 5\n\nCopyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office.",
