      "text": "You are absolutely correct! My apologies for that significant mistranslation. \"Faslaa\" in this context refers to uninhabited islands, not atolls. Thank you for pointing out this crucial error.\n\nI will now redo the translation with the correct understanding.\n\n**Laws of the Maldives**\n\n**Law on Maldivian Uninhabited Islands**\n\n**(Including the 1st Amendment to this Law)**\n\n**Law on Maldivian Uninhabited Islands**\n\n**Introduction and Title**\n1.\n(a) This is the law concerning the gifting of Maldivian uninhabited islands in ownership, their demarcation, leasing for purposes other than tourism, planting and cutting of trees on uninhabited islands, and other matters related to uninhabited islands.\n(b) This law shall be called the \"Law on Maldivian Uninhabited Islands.\"\n\n**Gifting of Uninhabited Islands in Ownership**\n**Gifting and Demarcation of Uninhabited Islands in Ownership**\n2.\n(a) Out of the uninhabited islands falling within an administrative district, excluding those uninhabited islands specified in section (b) of this article, other uninhabited islands shall be gifted in ownership and demarcated to various parties by the Ministry entrusted with the responsibility of implementing agricultural policies, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n(b) Out of the uninhabited islands falling within an administrative district, uninhabited islands that fall within the jurisdiction of an inhabited island or city shall be gifted in ownership and demarcated to various parties by the council to which that inhabited island or city belongs, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n(c) The principles to be followed in the gifting and demarcation of uninhabited islands under sections (a) and (b) of this article shall be stipulated in the regulations formulated by the Ministry entrusted with the responsibility of implementing agricultural policies, under this law.\n(d) Notwithstanding anything stated otherwise in section (a) of this article, it is not prohibited by this law for the implementation of matters concerning the gifting of uninhabited islands in ownership to be entrusted to a council, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Management and Upkeep of Uninhabited Islands**\n3.\nParties who have been gifted uninhabited islands in ownership shall plant trees on those uninhabited islands and maintain them in accordance with this law and the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Responsibility of Parties Gifted in Ownership**\n4.\nThe responsibilities and other principles related to matters concerning uninhabited islands gifted in ownership shall be stipulated in the regulations established under this law by the party holding ownership of the respective uninhabited island.\n\n**Gifting or Leasing of Uninhabited Islands Gifted in Ownership to a Third Party**\n5.\n(a) It is prohibited for any party to gift in ownership to another party, lease, or transfer the responsibility for the management of an uninhabited island that has been gifted in ownership.\n(b) Notwithstanding anything stated otherwise in section (a) of this article, this law does not prohibit the management of an uninhabited island gifted in ownership by employing individuals as employees of the party managing the uninhabited island, for the purpose of maintaining that uninhabited island.\n\n**Extraction of Stone, Sand, and Coral from Uninhabited Islands**\n8.\n(a) Extraction of stone from the shorelines and lagoons of uninhabited islands gifted in ownership is prohibited. This article does not prohibit dredging of the outlet of an uninhabited island or excavating a lagoon, with the permission of the relevant ministry, in accordance with government regulations.\n(b) Sand and coral shall be extracted from uninhabited islands gifted in ownership and from the shorelines and lagoons of such uninhabited islands only after obtaining written permission for the activity, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Demarcation of Uninhabited Islands Gifted in Ownership**\n9.\n(a) If an uninhabited island gifted in ownership needs to be taken by the government for government purposes before the expiry of the gifting period, the Ministry or the Council has the right to revoke the gifting agreement and demarcate the gifted uninhabited island, after giving 30 (thirty) days\u0027 notice to the party to whom the uninhabited island was gifted in ownership.\n(b) If the party to whom an uninhabited island has been gifted in ownership violates this law, or any regulation established under this law, or the agreement related to the gifting of that uninhabited island, the Ministry or the Council has the right to demarcate the uninhabited island from the party to whom it was gifted in ownership, after giving notice.\n(c) In the event of demarcation of an uninhabited island gifted in ownership from the party to whom it was gifted in ownership, under sections (a) and (b) of this article, no compensation shall be provided to that party.\n(d) In the event of demarcation of an uninhabited island gifted in ownership from the party to whom it was gifted in ownership, under sections (a) and (b) of this article, if any movable property of that party is located on the uninhabited island, the Ministry or the Council shall grant a period determined by them for the removal of such property from the uninhabited island. Furthermore, such a determined period shall be stated in the notice issued under sections (a) and (b) of this article.\n\n**Leasing of Uninhabited Islands**\n**Leasing of Uninhabited Islands**\n11.\n(a) Uninhabited islands shall be leased under this law, in accordance with the regulations established under this law, in one of the following two ways:\n(1) By giving it to the party who submits the most suitable proposal, following a public announcement as per the regulations established under this law, and in accordance with the principles stipulated in those regulations.\n(2) By giving it to a party who meets the conditions specified in the regulations established under this law, upon submission of a detailed report concerning the intended activity on the island, as per those regulations.\n(b) Uninhabited islands within the jurisdiction of an inhabited island or city, for purposes other than development as an industrial island for fishing, agriculture, or other industrial purposes, shall be leased by the Ministry entrusted with the responsibility of implementing those industries, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n(c) The regulations mentioned in section (b) of this article shall stipulate the principles for categorizing industrial islands.\n(d) Uninhabited islands within the jurisdiction of an inhabited island or city, for purposes other than development as an industrial island for fishing, agriculture, or other industrial purposes, shall be leased by the Ministry entrusted with the responsibility of implementing those industries, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n(e) The regulations mentioned in section (b) of this article shall stipulate the principles for categorizing industrial islands.\n(f) Uninhabited islands within the jurisdiction of an inhabited island or city, excluding those for development as industrial islands, shall be leased for other purposes by the council to which that inhabited island or city belongs, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Conditions for Leasing Uninhabited Islands Without Public Announcement**\n12.\nAn uninhabited island shall be leased under section (b) of Article 11 of this Law only if the following conditions are met:\n(a) The proposed activity on the island is beneficial to the Maldives, or beneficial to the citizens of Maldives.\n(b) The applicant for the island possesses the capability to carry out the proposed activity on the island.\n(c) The applicant for the island has access to the funds required to carry out the proposed activity on the island.\n\n**Leasing Period for Uninhabited Islands**\n13.\n(a) Islands leased under Article 11 of this law shall be leased for a period of 21 (twenty-one) calendar years, commencing from the date the island is handed over to the lessee.\n(b) Notwithstanding anything stated otherwise in section (a) of this article, this law does not prohibit the leasing of an uninhabited island for a period shorter than the period specified in that letter, or for a period not exceeding 50 (fifty) years, in the following circumstances:\n(1) If the period for which the applicant requests to lease the island is shorter than 21 (twenty-one) years, and the Ministry concerned deems it acceptable to lease for that period, the Ministry has the authority to do so.\n(2) In the case of an island leased for a period of 21 (twenty-one) years, if the party who leased the island wishes to continue the work being carried out on the island after the expiry of the lease period, and applies to extend the lease period, the Ministry has the authority to lease the island for a total period of 50 (fifty) years, including the initial 21 (twenty-one) year lease period. Furthermore, if an extension of the lease period is requested in this manner, the applicant must submit the request to the relevant Ministry 12 (twelve) months before the expiry of the current lease period.\n(c) The conditions that must be met by a party applying to lease an island, and the procedures to be followed when applying for a lease, shall be stipulated in the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Lease Agreement for Uninhabited Islands**\n14.\nUninhabited islands shall be leased under Article 11 of this Law through an agreement between the relevant Ministry or Council and the party leasing the island. This agreement must include the following:\n(a) The lease period.\n(b) The amount of rent and the method of payment.\n(c) The activity to be carried out on the island and the method of carrying it out.\n(d) The procedure to be followed if the lessee violates the agreement.\n(e) The method by which the agreement can be terminated.\n(f) The action to be taken regarding buildings and property on the island upon the expiry or termination of the agreement.\n\n**Termination of Leased Uninhabited Island Without Two Years\u0027 Notice Before Expiry**\n15.\nAn uninhabited island leased under Article 11 of this Law shall not be terminated from the lessee without providing at least two years\u0027 notice, unless required for the defense of the Maldives.\n\n**Sale of Investment Made on an Island**\n16.\n(a) An investment made on an island leased under Article 11 of this Law can be sold by the lessee to another party only after the investment has reached a level acceptable to the relevant Ministry, and with written permission from the Ministry or Council that leased the island.\n(b) If an investment made on an island is sold in accordance with section (a) of this article, the lease agreement between the lessee and the relevant Ministry or Council can be amended to transfer to the party purchasing the investment, for the duration of the agreement.\n\n**Leasing to a Third Party**\n17.\nAn island leased under Article 11 of this Law can be leased by the lessee to another party only after the activity proposed to be carried out on the island has commenced and reached a level acceptable in accordance with the standards stipulated in the regulations established under this law, and with written permission from the Ministry or Council that leased the island.\n\n**Uninhabited Islands Currently Operating Various Activities**\n18.\nFor uninhabited islands gifted in ownership within administrative districts, that are operating various activities with the permission of the relevant Ministry at the time this law comes into effect, to be considered as islands leased under Article 11 of this Law, the party holding ownership of the uninhabited island must submit a proposal to the relevant Ministry within one year from the date this law comes into effect and enter into an agreement as described in Article 14 of this Law.\n\n**Exemptions**\n19.\nUninhabited islands designated for state purposes, uninhabited islands on which the government directly implements various projects, uninhabited islands on which companies with 100% government shareholding operate various activities, and uninhabited islands on which foreign parties and the government jointly operate various activities, shall be exempt from the principles stated in Article 11 of this Law.\n\n**Uninhabited Islands Leased Before the Commencement of This Law**\n20.\nUninhabited islands that have been leased by the relevant Ministry under an agreement for a specified period before this law comes into effect shall not be altered due to this law for the duration of their lease. The lease period for such uninhabited islands shall be considered from the date the lease period stipulated in the agreement commences.\n\n**Leasing of Land or Parts of an Uninhabited Island**\n21.\nThis law does not prohibit the leasing of land or parts of an uninhabited island in accordance with a mechanism determined by the government.\n\n**General Principles for Uninhabited Islands Not Falling Within the Jurisdiction of an Island or City Council**\n21-1.\n(a) The President shall designate uninhabited islands that fall within an administrative district but are not within the jurisdiction of an inhabited island or city, for gifting in ownership, for development as industrial islands, for leasing for other purposes, and for other various uses.\n(b) Uninhabited islands falling within an administrative district but not within the jurisdiction of an inhabited island or city shall be handed over to a council, after obtaining permission from the relevant government Ministry.\n(c) The principles and procedures to be followed in granting the permission mentioned in section (b) of this article shall be stipulated in the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Public Access**\n**Access to Uninhabited Islands**\n21-2.\n(a) Entry to any uninhabited island gifted in ownership or leased uninhabited island, or access to the lagoon area of such uninhabited island as defined in the regulations established under this law, is prohibited without written permission from the party to whom the uninhabited island is gifted in ownership or the lessee.\n(b) Notwithstanding anything stated otherwise in section (a) of this article, this law does not prohibit the following parties from accessing uninhabited islands gifted in ownership or leased uninhabited islands, or their lagoons, free of charge, under the following circumstances:\n(1) With permission from the relevant Ministry or written permission from the relevant Ministry;\n(2) Entry to an uninhabited island gifted in ownership or its lagoon by the party who leased the uninhabited island;\n(3) In the performance of legal duties by security services;\n(4) For the purpose of saving lives and property due to adverse weather conditions, distress, or maritime incidents, or in any other emergency situation.\n\n**Cutting and Removal of Trees from Uninhabited Islands**\n21-3.\nTrees shall be cut, removed, or transported from one place to another on an uninhabited island gifted in ownership or a leased uninhabited island, in accordance with the regulations established under this law and the relevant laws and regulations formulated concerning environmental protection.\n\n**Non-Applicability of This Law to Uninhabited Islands Leased for Tourism Purposes**\n21-4.\nThe principles outlined in this law shall not apply to uninhabited islands leased for tourism purposes.\n\n**Action Against Parties Violating the Law**\n21-5.\n(a) Unless otherwise stipulated in this law, the Ministry has the authority to take the following measures against parties who violate this law or any regulation established under this law, commensurate with the extent of the violation and in accordance with the principles stipulated in the regulations established under this law:\n(1) In relation to an uninhabited island gifted in ownership, if the violation is committed by the party to whom the uninhabited island is gifted in ownership, a fine not exceeding MVR 1,000,000 (one million Rufiyaa) may be imposed, and penalties as stipulated in the agreement related to the gifting of the uninhabited island shall be applied, depending on the severity of the violation committed.\n(2) In relation to a leased uninhabited island, if the violation is committed by the lessee, a fine not exceeding MVR 1,000,000 (one million Rufiyaa) may be imposed, and penalties as stipulated in the agreement related to the leasing of the uninhabited island shall be applied, depending on the severity of the violation committed.\n(3) In relation to uninhabited islands other than those gifted in ownership or leased uninhabited islands, a fine not exceeding MVR 1,000,000 (one million Rufiyaa) may be imposed on the party committing the violation, depending on the severity of the act.\n(b) The regulations established under section (a) of this article shall detail the amounts of fines and the procedures for imposing fines based on the severity of the violation.\n(c) If an act committed by any party in violation of this law or any regulation established under this law constitutes a criminal offense, the Ministry shall report the matter to the relevant authorities for investigation. Furthermore, if such an act is defined as a criminal offense under the Penal Code of the Maldives, this law does not preclude the filing of criminal charges against the perpetrator under the Penal Code of the Maldives, in addition to the administrative penalties imposed under this law.\n\n**Making of Regulations**\n22.\nUnless otherwise stipulated in this law, the following regulations shall be made and implemented by the following parties:\n(a) Regulations concerning uninhabited islands gifted in ownership, and uninhabited islands leased for fishing and agricultural purposes, shall be made and implemented by the Ministry entrusted with the responsibility of implementing agricultural policies.\n(b) Regulations concerning uninhabited islands leased for economic purposes shall be made and implemented by the Ministry entrusted with the responsibility of implementing economic policies.\n(c) Regulations concerning uninhabited islands leased for other purposes shall be made and implemented by a Ministry designated by the President.\n\n**Repealed Laws**\n23.\nUpon the commencement of this law, Law Number 29/79 (Law on Planting of Trees on Maldivian Islands, Cutting of Trees, Uninhabited Islands, and Structures such as Govaafal) and Law Number 30/78 (Law on Prohibited Activities concerning Government Uninhabited Islands, Govaafal-like Lands, and Government Timber) shall be repealed.\n\nLaw Number: 20/98\nCommencement Date: 22 July 1998\nAmendment Number: 1\n\nCopyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office.",
