      "text": "You are absolutely correct to point out the error. \"Faslaa\" indeed refers to uninhabited islands, and \"Mihun Uleya Rasrasheh\" refers to inhabited islands. My apologies for the repeated mistake.\n\nHere is the corrected translation, focusing on \"inhabited islands\":\n\n**Laws of the Maldives**\n\n**Law on Trees on Inhabited Islands**\n\n**Law on Trees on Inhabited Islands**\n\n**Introduction and Title**\n1.\n(a) This is the law concerning the planting and cutting of trees on inhabited islands of the Maldives, excluding Malé, and concerning the ownership of trees on those islands.\n(b) This law shall be called the \"Law on Trees on Inhabited Islands.\"\n\n**Planting of Trees**\n2.\nTrees shall be planted in areas of inhabited islands, other than residential plots leased for living, Waqf lands, and lands handed over to various parties for different purposes, in designated locations determined by the Ministry of Atoll Administration, after obtaining permission from the Island Office.\n\n**Public Trees**\n3.\n(a) Trees that are considered government trees at the time this law comes into effect on inhabited islands shall be considered public trees after the commencement of this law.\n(b) Trees that are considered public trees of an island at the time this law comes into effect, and trees planted and grown as public trees of that island by the island office of that atoll, in accordance with the arrangements made by the Ministry of Atoll Administration, and all trees growing on that island other than private trees of individuals, shall be considered public trees of that island.\n\n**Private Trees**\n4.\nTrees planted on residential plots obtained for living, trees planted on lands handed over to various parties for different purposes, trees that legally or religiously belong to the owner at the time of receiving a residential plot, and trees planted by individuals on their own initiative in areas other than residential plots or lands handed over to them, in accordance with Article 2 of this law, shall be the trees of the person registered for that plot or the party to whom the land was handed over. If planted in any other location, they shall be the trees of the person who planted them.\n\n**Registration of Private Trees**\n5.\n(a) Private trees planted by individuals, in accordance with Article 2 of this law, shall be registered at the Island Office of the respective island, according to the method determined by the Ministry of Atoll Administration. Agricultural produce, fruits, or cereals planted on agricultural land shall be considered registered under this article upon the registration of the agricultural land.\n(b) Regarding trees planted before the commencement of this law in areas of inhabited islands other than residential plots leased for living and lands handed over to various parties for different purposes, any tree whose ownership has not been registered at the Island Office of that island in accordance with regulations, must be submitted to the Island Office and registered within three years from the date this law comes into effect.\n(c) Disputes concerning the ownership of trees to be registered in accordance with section (b) of this article shall be resolved through legal proceedings presented to the court.\n(d) Trees planted before the commencement of this law in areas of inhabited islands other than residential plots leased for living and lands handed over to various parties for different purposes, whose ownership has been registered at the Island Office of that island in accordance with regulations, and trees whose ownership has not yet been determined by court proceedings as per section (c) of this article, shall be considered public trees, unless otherwise decided by the court, after the expiry of three years from the date this law comes into effect.\n\n**Leasing and Demarcation of Public Trees, and Entrustment of Public Tree Management**\n6.\nThe leasing of public trees on inhabited islands, their demarcation by the lessees, and the entrustment of public tree management to various parties, shall be carried out by the Ministry of Atoll Administration or entities designated by the Ministry, in accordance with regulations established by the Ministry of Atoll Administration.\n\n**Maintenance of Public Trees**\n7.\nParties leasing public trees on inhabited islands shall maintain those trees in accordance with the regulations established by the Ministry of Atoll Administration.\n\n**Cutting of Public Trees**\n8.\nThe cutting of public trees, as referred to in Article 3 of this law, shall be carried out in accordance with a procedure determined by the Ministry of Atoll Administration, with the advice of the Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture.\n\n**Pruning of Fruit-Bearing Trees**\n9.\nFruit-bearing trees among the public trees on inhabited islands may be pruned, excluding types of trees for which pruning is prohibited by the Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture. Such pruning shall be done after obtaining permission from the Island Office of the respective island, in consultation with the Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture.\n\n**Authority to Designate Protected Trees**\n10.\nThe Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture has the authority to identify and designate as protected trees, any trees on inhabited islands that are over 50 years old, or any species of tree or palm that needs to be preserved in the Maldives, and to establish regulations for the management of such protected trees.\n\n**Prohibited Actions Related to Trees**\n11.\nThe following actions related to trees on inhabited islands are prohibited:\n(a) Any person, other than those specifically authorized by the government, cutting, pruning, reducing, or adding to the numbers or marks affixed by the government on trees.\n(b) Cutting trees in areas outside residential plots, other than uprooting them, unless otherwise stipulated by the government for environmental protection.\n(c) Applying lime or other substances to public trees during cutting to check for rot or decay.\n(d) Pruning trees or timber that the Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture has prohibited from pruning.\n(e) Cutting protected trees designated by the Ministry of Fisheries and Agriculture, or taking any action that may cause damage to such trees in any other way.\n\n**Penalties**\n12.\n(a) Any person who commits an act prohibited under Article 11 of this law shall be liable to a fine not exceeding MVR 5,000, or imprisonment for a period not exceeding six months, or house arrest.\n(b) Any person who commits an act in violation of this law, other than those offenses for which a penalty is prescribed in section (a) of this article, shall be liable to a fine not exceeding MVR 1,000.\n\n**Making of Regulations**\n13.\nRegulations required under this law, other than those explicitly stated to be made by specific parties, shall be made and implemented by the party or parties designated by the President.\n\n**Repealed Laws**\n14.\nUpon the commencement of this law, Law Number 7/70J (Law on Government Timber 1970) and Law Number 5/92 (Law on Planting of Trees on Inhabited Islands of the Maldives) shall be repealed.\n\nLaw Number: 21/98\nCommencement Date: 22 July 1998\n\nCopyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office.",
