      "text": "My sincere apologies for the repeated errors. I am still under development and learning to process nuanced legal terminology correctly. The term \"Faslaa\" indeed refers to uninhabited islands, and \"Banduara Gothi\" refers to government-allocated residential land. I will ensure to be more careful with these distinctions going forward.\n\nHere is the corrected translation, accurately reflecting the provisions regarding land and property, with \"Banduara Gothi\" translated as \"government-allocated residential land\" and other relevant terms.\n\n**Laws of the Maldives**\n\n**Land Law of the Maldives**\n\n**(Including the 8th Amendment to this Law)**\n\n**Land Law of the Maldives**\n\n**Introduction and Title**\n1.\n(a) This is the law concerning the allocation of land in the Maldives for various purposes and uses, the granting of government-allocated residential land, the management, use, sale, gifting, and leasing of government-allocated residential land and private land, and other related matters.\n(b) This law shall be called the \"Land Law of the Maldives.\"\n\n**Conducting Land-Related Transactions**\n2.\nAll transactions concerning land and property in the Maldives, including the granting, acquisition, ownership, sale, leasing, use, and management of land and property, shall be conducted in accordance with this law.\n\n**Policy Determining Authority and Land Allocating Authority**\n3.\n(a) The President, in consultation with the Cabinet, shall determine the land policy of the Maldives.\n(b) In accordance with the land policy mentioned in section (a) of this article, the President shall allocate land for various purposes and uses, and shall transfer allocated land from one category to another.\n\n**Purposes and Uses for Which Land is Allocated**\n4.\nLand shall be allocated in accordance with Article 3 of this law for the following purposes and uses:\n(a) For the construction of houses and buildings for residential purposes.\n(b) For economic purposes.\n(c) For social purposes.\n(d) For environmental protection.\n(e) For state purposes.\n\n**Land Handed Over to Ministries and Other Parties, and Land Under the Ownership of Councils**\n**Handing Over of Land to Ministries and State Institutions**\n5.\n(a) Land allocated for various purposes and uses, in accordance with Articles 3 and 4 of this law, shall be handed over to the respective Ministries and State institutions in accordance with Law No. 7/2010 (Decentralization Law of the Maldives).\n(b) The principles concerning the handover and demarcation of land handed over to respective Ministries and State institutions under section (a) of this article shall be stipulated in the regulations established under this law, in accordance with Law No. 7/2010 (Decentralization Law of the Maldives).\n\n**Land Register**\n6.\n(a) The Ministry shall compile and maintain the Land Register of the Maldives in accordance with this law.\n(b) The Land Register of the Maldives mentioned in section (a) of this article shall include the following information:\n(1) The manner in which land has been allocated for various purposes and uses, in accordance with Articles 3 and 4 of this law.\n(2) The location of the land and its dimensions.\n(3) The Ministries and State institutions to which land is handed over, the purpose of handover, and the date of handover, in accordance with Article 5 of this law.\n(4) The owners of private plots and lands, and the respective owners.\n(5) Information on lands under the ownership of councils.\n(6) Any other information specified in the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Conducting Land-Related Transactions**\n7.\n(a) Ministries and State institutions to which land is handed over, in accordance with Article 5 of this law, shall grant, lease, and conduct other land-related transactions in accordance with this law, and the laws and regulations governing land allocated for various purposes and uses.\n(b) Councils shall grant, lease, and conduct other land-related transactions concerning land under their ownership, in accordance with this law, and the laws and regulations governing land allocated for various purposes and uses.\n\n**Granting of Land for Various Purposes and Uses**\n8.\n(a) Land handed over to various Ministries and State institutions in accordance with Article 5 of this law shall be used, and granted or leased to various parties, in accordance with the Land Use Plan established for the island or city where the land is located, and for the purpose or use for which the land has been allocated in accordance with Articles 3 and 4 of this law.\n(b) Lands under the ownership of councils shall be used, and granted or leased to various parties, in accordance with the Land Use Plan established for the island or city where the land is located, and for the purpose or use for which the land has been allocated in accordance with Articles 3 and 4 of this law.\n\n**Granting of Land for Non-Residential Purposes and Transactions Related to Land Granted for Economic Purposes**\n9.\n(a) Land handed over to respective Ministries and State institutions under Article 5 of this law, or land under the ownership of councils, other than land allocated for residential purposes under Articles 3 and 4 of this law, shall be granted in accordance with the provisions of this law, regulations established under this law, and laws and regulations governing land allocated for various purposes and uses, through a written agreement between the Ministry, institution, or council, and the party to whom the land is granted.\n(b) A party to whom land is granted under section (a) of this article may use and exercise rights related to that land in accordance with this law, laws and regulations governing land allocated for various purposes and uses, and regulations established under these laws, for the period for which the land is granted and in the manner specified in the agreement for granting the land.\n(c) Land allocated for economic purposes under Article 4 of this law and handed over to respective Ministries or State institutions under Article 5 of this law, or land under the ownership of councils, may be transacted for commercial purposes in accordance with regulations established under this law. Such land handed over to Ministries or State institutions, or land under council ownership, may be sold or leased to a third party by those parties, provided it does not contravene the Constitution and this law.\n(d) The rights of the party purchasing or leasing land under section (c) of this article, and rights associated with that land, shall be registered in favor of those parties in accordance with their transactions and the regulations established under this law. The Ministry, State institution, or council granting the land shall grant the following rights to the second party in accordance with the agreement with that party:\n(1) To develop the land and use it for various purposes, real estate business, and other business purposes;\n(2) To sell, gift, or exchange the land or part of it to another party, with the written permission of the Ministry, State institution, or council that granted the land, in accordance with the rights vested in that party related to the land;\n(3) To mortgage the legal rights associated with the land or any construction on the land, with the written permission of the Ministry, State institution, or council that granted the land;\n(4) To use the land or the legal rights associated with part of the land as various financial and business channels.\n(e) The Ministry or State institution that grants land to Ministries or State institutions under section (c) of this article shall be responsible for registering such land and any constructions on that land in accordance with this law and the regulations established under this law.\n(f) Articles 10 through 36 of this law shall be exempted from transactions related to land granted to Ministries under section (c) of this article.\n(g) If any land or part of land or any construction on that land, granted to Ministries under section (c) of this article, is sold, 15% (fifteen percent) of the sale price of that land or construction shall be paid to the government as tax by the party selling the land or construction. This does not include sales made by the government or the relevant Ministry as the seller of the land.\n(h) The Ministry has the authority to make and implement regulations concerning the matters specified in sections (c), (d), (e), and (g) of this article.\n(i) The regulations mentioned in section (h) of this article must be made and published in the Government Gazette within 3 (three) months from the date of commencement of the law bringing the 4th amendment to the Land Law of the Maldives (Law No. 1/2002).\n\n**Granting of Government-Allocated Residential Land**\n**Granting of Residential Land**\n10.\nResidential land from land allocated for the construction of houses and buildings for residential purposes under Articles 3 and 4 of this law shall be granted in accordance with the principles announced publicly and regulations established by the Ministry. In Malé, this shall be done by the Malé Municipality upon the recommendation of the Ministry. In other islands, this shall be done by the Island Office of the respective atoll upon the recommendation of the Ministry of Atoll Development.\n\n**Manner of Granting Residential Land**\n11.\nGovernment-allocated residential land shall be granted under Article 10 of this law in the following manner:\n(a) Government-allocated residential land shall be granted to Maldivian citizens who have not received a government-allocated residential plot, or a private plot, or a part of a government-allocated plot or private plot divided according to Article 15 of this law, or a flat in a government-built building, or a flat in a multi-story building. However, if a person who has received a part of a government-allocated plot or private plot divided according to Article 15 of this law, relinquishes that part or makes its relinquishment a condition, this article does not prevent the granting of a government-allocated residential land to that person.\n(b) Residential land granted after the commencement of this law shall not exceed 4,000 square feet.\n(c) After the commencement of this law, no person shall be granted more than one residential plot in any single island. A government-allocated residential plot may be granted to a person in an island other than the island where they already hold a government-allocated residential plot, by paying a rent determined by the government, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n(d) Government-allocated residential land shall be granted in accordance with this law and the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Application for Government-Allocated Residential Land**\n12.\n(a) Applications for residential land from land allocated for the construction of houses and buildings for residential purposes under Articles 3 and 4 of this law may be submitted for plots in designated areas, if such allocation has been decided and publicly announced. Applications shall be made by completing the application form and submitting it to the office from which the public announcement was issued.\n(b) Any person who meets the conditions specified in this law and the regulations established under this law may apply for a government-allocated residential land, as per section (a) of this article, when a public announcement is made for the allocation of government-allocated residential land.\n\n**Registration of Plots and Buildings**\n13.\n(a) Every government-allocated residential plot granted shall be registered at the office granting the plot in accordance with the regulations established under this law, and a registration certificate for the plot shall be issued to the party to whom the plot is granted.\n(b) Every building constructed on a government-allocated residential plot granted under section (a) of this article shall be registered at the office granting the plot in accordance with the regulations established under this law, and a registration certificate for the building shall be issued.\n\n**Revocation of Government-Allocated Residential Land**\n14.\n(a) If a person to whom a government-allocated residential land is granted does not commence residing on the plot within 5 years from the date of granting, the government reserves the right to revoke the plot from the person to whom it was granted.\n(b) If a person who has been granted a government-allocated residential land repeatedly violates this law, or violates any condition stipulated at the time of granting the plot, the government reserves the right to revoke the plot from the person to whom it was granted, in accordance with the law.\n\n**Death of the Recipient of Government-Allocated Residential Land**\n15.\n(a) If a person to whom a government-allocated residential land is granted dies, the building on that plot and the immovable property may be divided into separate plots among the legal heirs.\n(b) If a person to whom a government-allocated residential land is granted dies, the building on that plot and the immovable property may be registered in the names of all legal heirs, if they so request, by establishing separate registrations.\n\n**Purchase, Sale, and Gifting of Government-Allocated Residential Land**\n**Purchase of Government-Allocated Residential Land**\n16.\nA party to whom a government-allocated residential land is granted may purchase that plot by paying the full price at once, or by installments, in accordance with the regulations established under this law and the procedure for payment of the price. The price of the plot purchased in this manner shall be determined in accordance with section (a) of Article 18 of this law.\n\n**Gifting or Bequest**\n17.\nA building or part of a building on a government-allocated residential plot may be gifted or bequeathed in the following manner:\n(a) The recipient of the gift or bequest shall be the spouse, child, mother, father, or the grandchild of a deceased child of the person making the gift or bequest.\n(b) If none of the parties mentioned in section (a) of this article object, or if any of these parties are deceased, the gift or bequest may be made to a grandchild of the donor or to a relative of the donor by paternal or maternal lineage.\n(c) The principles stipulated in section (a) of Article 11 of this law shall not apply to gifts or bequests made to the parties mentioned in section (a) of this article. Unless otherwise stated in this law, gifts or bequests to the parties mentioned in section (b) of this article shall be made in accordance with the principles stipulated in section (a) of Article 11 of this law.\n(d) A gift or bequest from the parties mentioned in section (a) of this article may be made to specific parties only if other parties mentioned in section (a) of this article have sufficient land. If other parties mentioned in section (a) of this article do not have sufficient land, a gift or bequest may be made to specific parties without their objection. However, in cases where the gift or bequest is to the children of the donor or to the children of the donor\u0027s deceased children, the spouse, mother, or father of the donor may object, but this article does not prevent the gift or bequest to these individuals.\n(e) The person making the gift or bequest, and the legally dependent individuals of that person, must have alternative residential arrangements.\n(f) The recipient of the gift or bequest must be a citizen of the Maldives.\n\n**Purchase of Residential Plot and Taxes Payable to the Government**\n18.\nA government-allocated residential plot, which has been purchased by the party to whom it was granted in accordance with Article 16 of this law, may be sold to other parties in accordance with the principles of public announcement and valuation determined by the Ministry through regulations established under this law, as follows:\n(a) The person wishing to sell the plot must have alternative residential arrangements, and their legally dependent individuals must also have alternative residential arrangements.\n(b) The party purchasing the plot must be a Maldivian citizen, or a company registered in the Maldives where 100% of the shareholders are Maldivians, or a partnership, or a cooperative society, or an association or group registered in the Maldives comprising 100% Maldivians.\n(c) Any share of a company registered in the Maldives, where 100% of the shareholders are Maldivians, which has purchased a plot or land, cannot sell any portion of its shares to a foreign party.\n(d) If any plot or land is sold, 15% of the sale price of that plot or land shall be paid to the government as tax by the party selling the plot or land.\n\n**Transactions Related to Immovable Property and Taxes Payable to the Government**\n19.\n(a) Any plot or land cannot be sold separately from the building on it. Similarly, any plot or land cannot be mortgaged separately from the building on it.\n(b) Multi-story buildings are considered separate entities, and therefore transactions related to multi-story buildings and their flats are exempted from section (a) of this article.\n(c) A multi-story building or a flat in a multi-story building shall be sold in accordance with the principles of public announcement and valuation determined by the Ministry through regulations established under this law, as follows:\n(1) The person wishing to sell a multi-story building or a flat in a multi-story building must have alternative residential arrangements, and their legally dependent individuals must also have alternative residential arrangements.\n(2) The party purchasing a multi-story building or a flat in a multi-story building must be a Maldivian citizen, or a company registered in the Maldives where 100% of the shareholders are Maldivians, or a partnership, or a cooperative society, or an association or group registered in the Maldives comprising 100% Maldivians.\n(d) Any share of a company registered in the Maldives, where 100% of the shareholders are Maldivians, which has purchased a multi-story building or a flat in a multi-story building, cannot sell any portion of its shares to a foreign party.\n(e) If a multi-story building or a flat in a multi-story building is sold, 15% of the sale price of that building or flat shall be paid to the government as tax by the party selling the building or flat.\n(f) A building or a flat in a multi-story building may be gifted or bequeathed in accordance with Article 17 of this law.\n(g) Parties selling flats under social housing projects designated by the government are exempted from paying the tax payable to the government under this article.\n(h) If a person purchasing a flat in a multi-story building under section (d) of this article is a Maldivian citizen, and this is the first time they are purchasing such a flat, the party selling the flat is exempted from paying the tax payable to the government under section (e) of this article.\n(i) In the situation described in section (h) of this article, the ownership of land by the person purchasing a flat in a multi-story building in any part of the Maldives shall not be considered an impediment to that person receiving the exemption mentioned in that letter.\n\n**Conditional Granting and Gifting**\n20.\n(a) After the commencement of this law, residential land granted by the government, or part of it, or any building constructed on such land, or part of a building, cannot be granted conditionally to any party.\n(b) This article does not prohibit the enforcement of registered agreements related to conditional granting entered into before the commencement of this law. Furthermore, a person who receives a plot under a registered conditional land grant agreement entered into before the commencement of this law shall be issued a registration for that plot.\n\n**Registration for the Purchaser or Recipient**\n21.\nIf a plot is sold or gifted in accordance with Articles 17 and 18 of this law, the plot shall be registered in the name of the purchaser or recipient by the Malé Municipality in Malé, or by the Island Office of the respective island in other islands, and a registration certificate for the plot shall be issued.\n\n**Sale of Government-Allocated Residential Land by the Government**\n22.\n(a) Land allocated for the construction of houses and buildings for residential purposes under Articles 3 and 4 of this law and handed over to respective Ministries in accordance with Article 5 of this law may be sold by those Ministries to a third party in accordance with this law and the regulations established under this law.\n(b) The Ministries handing over land under section (a) of this article for sale to the public are not required to comply with Articles 10, 11, 12, and 18 of this law.\n(c) The land purchased by a third party from the Ministries under section (a) of this article and the rights associated with that land shall be registered in favor of those parties in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Private Land**\n**Applicability of This Law to Private Plots**\n23.\nThis law shall apply to all private land and plots existing in the Maldives before the commencement of this law, and also to government-allocated residential land purchased and made private after the commencement of this law.\n\n**Registration of Private Land and Plots**\n24.\n(a) Private land, plots, and buildings constructed on such plots shall be registered at the Malé Municipality in Malé, or at the Island Office of the respective island in other islands.\n(b) The registration of land, plots, and buildings registered in accordance with section (a) of this article shall be prepared in accordance with this law and the regulations established under this law, and issued to the owner of the plot.\n(c) If the ownership of private land or a plot registered in accordance with section (a) of this article changes, the registration of that land or plot shall be transferred to the party who acquired ownership, by submitting the legal document proving the change of ownership to the Malé Municipality in Malé, or to the Island Office of the respective island in other islands. Similarly, if the registered owner of private land or a plot dies, the registration of that land or plot shall be transferred to the party who acquired ownership, by submitting the legal document proving the succession of ownership to the Malé Municipality in Malé, or to the Island Office of the respective island in other islands, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Sale of Private Land and Plots**\n25.\nPrivate land and plots existing before the enactment of this law, and private land and plots made private after the commencement of this law, may be sold, gifted, bequeathed, or transferred in any other manner, in accordance with Articles 17 and 18 of this law and the conditions stipulated therein.\n\n**Death of the Owner of Private Land and Plots**\n26.\n(a) If the owner of private land or a plot dies, that land or plot may be divided into separate plots among their heirs.\n(b) If the owner of private land or a plot dies, the building on that land or plot, and the immovable property thereon, may be registered in the names of all legal heirs, if they so request, by establishing separate registrations.\n\n**Leasing of Private Plots and Use for Non-Residential Purposes**\n27.\nPrivate plots shall be leased, or used for non-residential purposes, in accordance with Article 28 (b), (c), (d), (e), and Article 30 of this law.\n\n**Leasing**\n**Leasing of Residential Land**\n28.\nGovernment-allocated residential plots, or parts of government-allocated residential plots, or buildings constructed on government-allocated residential plots, or parts of buildings, shall be leased for residential purposes in the following manner:\n(a) The lease period shall not exceed 50 (fifty) years.\n(b) The entire plot or the entire building constructed on the plot shall be leased after entering into an agreement between the lessor and the lessee, in accordance with the regulations established under this law regarding leasing.\n(c) If a part of a plot or a part of a building is leased for a period exceeding 1 year, the lease shall be granted after entering into an agreement in accordance with the regulations established under this law regarding the leasing of such premises.\n(d) Rooms for residential purposes, buildings, and premises constructed for leasing shall be registered at the Malé Municipality in Malé, or at the Island Office of the respective island in other islands, within 1 year from the date this law comes into effect.\n(e) Flats constructed and leased by government shareholding companies specifically for building houses and providing residential facilities are exempted from section (a) of this article.\n\n**Leasing for Non-Residential Purposes**\n29.\n(a) Government-allocated residential plots, or parts of government-allocated residential plots, or buildings constructed on such plots, or parts of buildings, may be leased for non-residential purposes, subject to the following conditions:\n(1) Obtaining permission from the Malé Municipality in Malé, or the Island Office of the respective island in other islands, for leasing a plot or part of a plot for non-residential purposes.\n(2) The purpose of the lease shall not be contrary to the government\u0027s policy regarding land use for that island.\n(b) A government-allocated residential plot, or part of a government-allocated residential plot, or a building constructed on such a plot, or part of a building, may be leased for non-residential purposes for a period not exceeding 50 (fifty) years, as specified in section (b) of this article.\n(c) Land granted for non-residential purposes under section (b) of this article may be used for activities permitted within the designated land use regulations for the area where the land is located.\n\n**Non-Residential Use**\n**Non-Residential Use**\n30.\n(a) A government-allocated residential plot may be used for non-residential purposes only after obtaining permission from the Malé Municipality in Malé, or the Island Office of the respective island in other islands.\n(b) Permission under section (a) of this article shall be granted only if the activity or purpose for which the plot is to be used is not contrary to the government\u0027s policy regarding land use for that island.\n\n**Multi-Story Building**\n**Multi-Story Building**\n31.\nA multi-story building is a building constructed with separate flats for more than one flat owner, and owned by more than one person.\n\n**Registration of a Building as a Multi-Story Building**\n32.\nIf any person or party wishes to convert a building constructed on their private land or a government-allocated residential plot into a multi-story building, that building shall be registered as a multi-story building in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Plot of a Multi-Story Building**\n33.\nEvery owner of a flat in a multi-story building shall be registered as the owner of the plot on which the building is constructed. If the land on which a multi-story building is constructed is government land, then every owner of a flat in such a building shall be registered as the person to whom the government-allocated land was granted.\n\n**Rights of the Purchaser of a Flat**\n34.\n(a) Upon the registration of a building as a multi-story building under Article 32 of this law, the owner of each flat in that building shall have the right to sell, gift, bequeath, or lease such flats in accordance with this law and the regulations established under this law.\n(b) A flat in a multi-story building on government-allocated land may be sold or gifted to a person other than the person to whom the land was granted by the government, only after obtaining written permission from the relevant government authority and in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Maintenance of Multi-Story Buildings and Land**\n35.\nThe owners of the multi-story building shall maintain the common areas and facilities within the multi-story building and manage matters related to those areas in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Relinquishment or Sale of a Flat**\n36.\nThe party who has received or purchased a flat in a multi-story building has the right to relinquish or sell that flat in accordance with the regulations established under this law. The person who purchases or receives such a relinquished or sold flat shall be registered as the owner of that flat in accordance with this law.\n\n**Other Matters**\n**Mortgaging**\n37.\n(a) Any land in the Maldives may be mortgaged if the party to whom the land is registered has the right to mortgage it, as follows:\n(1) If the land is obtained under an agreement as specified in Article 9 of this law, it may be mortgaged in accordance with the terms of that agreement.\n(2) A plot or land registered in the name of a party or parties may be mortgaged as follows:\n    (i) The mortgagee must be a commercial bank or a financial institution recognized by the government.\n    (ii) Before mortgaging, the mortgagor must explain the mortgage transaction and its consequences to the mortgagor in the presence of two independent witnesses.\n    (iii) If a plot registered in the names of more than one person, or a plot and the building on it, is being mortgaged, all parties registered for that plot must consent. However, if such a plot has been divided among its registered owners and this is marked in the plot registration, it is not necessary to obtain the consent of other registered parties for mortgaging the portion allocated to that person.\n    (iv) Every mortgage under this article must be registered at the office that granted the plot or land.\n    (v) Any mortgage under this article may be enforced in accordance with the regulations established under this law and the following conditions:\n        (1) The sale of any plot or land for the enforcement of a mortgage shall be conducted through a public bidding process organized by entities designated by the government, with court permission, in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n        (2) Unless otherwise agreed in writing by the mortgagor and the mortgagee, legal action must be taken to recover the loan amount within 1 year from the expiry date of the loan repayment period stipulated in the mortgage agreement.\n        (3) For matters where the loan repayment period expired before the commencement of the first amendment to the Land Law of the Maldives, legal action must be taken to recover the loan amount within 1 year from the commencement date of that amendment, unless otherwise agreed in writing by the mortgagor and the mortgagee.\n        (4) If a mortgagor wishes to sell the mortgage or part of the mortgage due to non-payment of the loan amount in a situation where a mortgage has been executed and a loan has been taken, this article does not prevent the mortgagor from approaching the court to sell the mortgage or part of the mortgage.\n    (vi) In cases where a plot or land or a building on land is mortgaged to more than one mortgage, priority in the enforcement of the mortgage shall be given in the order of registration of the mortgage under this article. For the enforcement of such mortgages executed before the commencement of the first amendment to the Land Law of the Maldives, priority shall be given according to the date of the mortgage agreement.\n    (vii) The proceeds from the sale of land or buildings for the enforcement of a mortgage under this article shall be utilized for the following purposes, in the following order:\n        (1) To reimburse the government for expenses incurred in organizing the bidding process as stated in sub-paragraph (v)(1) of this article.\n        (2) To pay taxes payable to the government under Article 18 of this law.\n        (3) To repay the loan taken against the mortgage.\n        (4) In the case of enforcing a mortgage on government land, to pay the government the value of the land as determined under this law.\n    (viii) If there are surplus funds after deducting the amounts specified in sub-paragraph (vii) of this article, such surplus funds shall be returned to the mortgagor.\n    (ix) In the event of selling government land for the enforcement of a mortgage under this article, ownership of that land shall be transferred to the mortgagee.\n    (x) Articles 18 (f) and (g) of this law shall not apply in cases of selling land or buildings for the enforcement of a mortgage under this article.\n    (xi) The enforcement of mortgages on buildings on government-allocated residential land executed before the commencement of the first amendment to the Land Law of the Maldives shall also be carried out in accordance with this article.\n\n**Waqf (Endowment)**\n38.\n(a) Any land in the Maldives, or any immovable property on land in the Maldives, may be endowed as Waqf, provided that such endowment is not contrary to the government\u0027s policy regarding land use for that island, and with written permission from the Ministry.\n(b) No land in Malé, or any immovable property on land in Malé, can be endowed as Waqf.\n\n**Discoveries During Excavation**\n39.\n(a) All natural resources on land in the Maldives, other than private trees, and all treasure trove, gold, silver, jewelry, currency, household items, archaeological artifacts, and all minerals found on land in the Maldives, are the property of the state.\n(b) If any jewelry, household items, currency, archaeological artifacts, or minerals mentioned in section (a) of this article are found on land in the Maldives, the finder shall immediately report the discovery to the Ministry of Finance and Treasury in Malé, or to the Island Office of the respective island in other islands.\n\n**Extraction of Sand and Stone**\n40.\nSand and stone may be extracted from government-allocated residential plots, lands, and private plots that have been granted to various parties, and sold or gifted, only with permission from the Malé Municipality in Malé, or the Island Office of the respective island in other islands, and in accordance with the regulations established under this law.\n\n**Property of Others on One\u0027s Land**\n41.\n(a) Buildings, trees, and other immovable property attached to the land, located on private land of another party or on government-allocated land granted to a person or party, shall be the property of the owner of that land or the party to whom the government-allocated land was granted, unless there is legal documentation proving otherwise.\n(b) No person other than the party to whom the government-allocated residential plot was granted shall construct a building on that plot.\n\n**Making of Regulations**\n42.\nRegulations required under this law shall be made and implemented by the party or parties designated by the President for that purpose.\n\n**Implementation of This Law**\n43.\nThis law shall come into effect one year from the date it is passed, ratified, and published in the Government Gazette.\n\n**Exemptions**\n44.\nTransactions involving government-allocated land under this law shall be exempted from Article 1 (k) of Law No. 9/68 (Law on Transfer of Ownership).\n\n**Definitions**\n45.\n(a) Unless the context otherwise requires, \"enforcement of mortgage\" in this law means the efforts made by the mortgagee to realize their rights due to the mortgagor\u0027s breach of any condition or promise made at the time of mortgaging.\n(b) \"Granting of residential land\" in this law refers to the government providing or granting government-allocated residential land free of charge, or by charging a fee, in accordance with the standards, conditions, and principles set by the government for providing or facilitating housing. It also includes land provided or granted by the government by charging a fee in accordance with the standards, conditions, and principles set by the government for providing or facilitating housing.\n(c) \"Granting of residential land\" as mentioned in section (b) of this article does not include land granted by the government for commercial purposes with the intention of making a profit.\n(d) \"Ministry\" refers to the government ministry responsible for overseeing all land-related matters.\n(e) \"Council\" refers to the council as defined in Law No. 7/2010 (Decentralization Law of the Maldives).\n\n**Repealed Laws**\n46.\nUpon the commencement of this law, Law No. 2/70J (Law on Transferring Waqf Land in Malé to Another Island and Prohibiting Waqf of Land in Malé), Law No. 28/71J (Law on Property of Others on Land Owned by One Party), Law No. 15/72J (Law on Acquisition by the Government of Uninhabited Land Without Proper Construction and Residence), Law No. 52/78 (Law on Registration of Plots, Lands, and Buildings in Malé), Law No. 55/78 (Law Prohibiting the Extraction, Gifting, and Sale of Sand and Stone from Government-Allocated Plots and Land in Malé), and Law No. 59/78 (Law on Objects Found During Excavation in the Maldives) shall be repealed.\n\nLaw Number: 1/2002\nCommencement Date: 23 May 2003\nAmendment Number: 8\n\nCopyright © 2023 Attorney General\u0027s Office.",
